#VLAYER.HLP
:vla:The Vlayer and Its Uses

The vlayer is an extra, global graphical layer (up to 32768
chars large), but it is never directly seen. It can only hold
character and color info. The vlayer acts like a workspace
allowing copying from/to overlay, copying from/to MZMs, copying
from vlayer to vlayer, reading/writing individual graphical
data to/from the vlayer, and reading strings from the vlayer.

Another important aspect of the vlayer is the ability to
reference a sprite to the vlayer.  This allows indirect display
of the vlayer through display of sprites. This can be
exploited to create the semblance of an extra overlay.

As for the vlayer's dimensions, it defaults to 256x128. If
these dimensions aren't adequate, the counters vlayer_width
and vlayer_height control its dimensions. Changing one will
make the other the largest it can be (if width was set
to 500, for example, height would be set to 65, for a total
workspace size of 32500).

To manipulate the vlayer, instead of using pure numbers in copy
commands, "#n" is used instead. For example, if copying a 2x2
block from 6,6 of the board to 0,0 of the vlayer is wanted, the
command would be:

~ecopy block 6 6 2 2 "#0" "#0"

Here are the vlayer copy functions:

Board to vlayer: ~ecopy block x1 y1 w h "#x2" "#y2"
Overlay to vlayer: ~ecopy overlay block x1 y1 w h "#x2" "#y2"
Vlayer to board: ~ecopy block "#x1" "#y1" w h x2 y2
Vlayer to overlay: copy overlay block "#x1" "#y1" w h x2 y2

In these, ~ecopy block~f and ~ecopy overlay block~f are interchangable.

Vlayer to MZM:
~ecopy (overlay) block "#x1" "#y1" w h "@name.mzm" m
Vlayer to string:
~ecopy (overlay) block "#x1" "#y1" w h "$stringN" c
Vlayer to itself:
~ecopy (overlay) block "#x1" "#y1" w h "#x2" "#y2"

There are several ways to give the vlayer working coordinates:

Pure numbers: "#xxx"
Counter value: "#&counter&"
Expressions: "#('counter' + x)"

MZMs can be placed on the vlayer by using p02. Example:

~eput "@visuals.mzm" image_file p02 x y

Reading and writing single characters or colors from the vlayer
requires the vch and vco counters.

For reading and writing characters use "vchX,Y".
For reading and writing colors use "vcoX,Y".

For example:

~eset "vch10,10" '+'~f sets the vlayer char at 10, 10 to a plus
sign.
~eset "vco10,10" 15~f sets the vlayer color at 10, 10 to white on
black.
~eset "temp" "vch10,10"~f sets temp to whatever the character at
10, 10 of the vlayer is.

Remember that the vlayer is global. If many vlayers are wanted,
liberal usage of MZM saving and loading will help to get around
this problem (though multiple MZMs may be needed if one vlayer
dimension is over 256 chars).

