#PARTIAL.HLP
:par:Partial Character Sets

Partial character sets are less than a full set, indeed, but
they only overwrite the characters they are told to. This
leaves the rest of the characters intact. Heavy animations and
changes that keep part of the character set intact (such as the
font) are two large reasons to use partial character sets.
There are three ways to save partial character sets.

~e#xxx prefix~f: This is for capturing characters from the
beginning of the char set. xxx is the size of the character
block you wish to save (in decimal), starting with character 1.
For example, #33initzone.chr will read chars 0 through 32 in
the current character set and save to the file 'initzone.chr'.

~e+xxx prefix~f: This is for capturing all charcters from a
user-specified starting point. xxx is the size of the starting
point of the file save (in decimal), saving all characters from
the start to 255. For example, +128halfset2.chr will read chars
128 through 255 in the current character set and save to the
file 'halfset2.chr'.

~e+xxx#yyy prefix~f: This combines both of the above methods. One
can save a char set of a specified size (decimal yyy) from a 
specified start in the current character set (decimal xxx).
For example, +170#28profile1.chr will save a 28-character size
block from characters 170 through 197 of the current char set.

To load partial character sets into your current set, you have
two options. You can firstly load it as you would a normal
character set; this replaces all charcters from the start of
the target character set until the end of the partial set.
Secondly, you can load the partial set into a non-0 position of
the target character set.  The @xxx prefix allows this; xxx is
the number (in decimal) of the first character to replace in
the target character set.

